NesInternalRam:0:scratch_ptr_lo:General-purpose ZP scratch pointer LO (project-wide default; 13 of 16 banks touch this). In the VM = computed-address + indirect-call target (was ptr0). Kept generic deliberately -- NOT VM-exclusive.
NesInternalRam:1:scratch_ptr_hi:General-purpose ZP scratch pointer HI (was ptr0).
NesInternalRam:2:vm_sp_lo:VM operand-stack pointer LO (was ptr1). Reset-inits to $FF -> $05FF stack base; VM frame alloc does vm_sp -= 9; syscall_dispatch reads params via (vm_sp),Y. CAVEAT: a few kernel syscalls (e.g. sram checksum $C5AA) transiently borrow $02/$03 as a scratch pointer.
NesInternalRam:3:vm_sp_hi:VM operand-stack pointer HI (was ptr1); reset-init to $05.
NesInternalRam:4:vm_fp_lo:VM frame-base pointer LO (was ptr2). Frame-local address = vm_fp + signed offset (the local/array access base; see vm_addr_ptr2_plus_word/sbyte).
NesInternalRam:5:vm_fp_hi:VM frame-base pointer HI (was ptr2).
NesInternalRam:6:vm_ip_lo:VM bytecode instruction-pointer LO (was ptr3). The dispatch loop does lda (vm_ip),Y / inc vm_ip to fetch opcodes + inline operands. Second-busiest indirect after scratch_ptr.
NesInternalRam:7:vm_ip_hi:VM bytecode instruction-pointer HI (was ptr3).
NesInternalRam:1C:ppu_queue_a_lo:Pointer LO into $0020 (PPU upload queue A?); reset-init = $20
NesInternalRam:1D:ppu_queue_a_hi:Pointer HI; reset-init = $00 (forms $0020)
NesInternalRam:1E:ppu_queue_b_lo:Pointer LO into $0030 (queue B?); reset-init = $30
NesInternalRam:1F:ppu_queue_b_hi:Pointer HI; reset-init = $00 (forms $0030)
NesInternalRam:50:brk_dispatch_id:Task ID for next BRK; IRQ handler reads this and indirect-JMPs through $C173+id*3
NesInternalRam:66:brk_scratch_lo:Cleared on every BRK dispatch entry
NesInternalRam:67:brk_scratch_hi:Cleared on every BRK dispatch entry
NesInternalRam:68:brk_jmp_target_lo:IRQ-computed indirect JMP target LO; reused later as general data-pointer LO (byte-meaning-by-context)
NesInternalRam:69:brk_jmp_target_hi:IRQ-computed indirect JMP target HI; reused as data-pointer HI
NesInternalRam:6E:p1_buttons:P1 held buttons (ABSS UDLR, MSB-first); written by controller_poll ($C628) every NMI
NesInternalRam:6F:p2_buttons:P2 held buttons (same format)
NesInternalRam:71:ppuctrl_shadow:PPUCTRL ($2000) shadow; the codebase never reads $2000 directly. Managed by $C6A6 ($C54F/nmi_off, $C68A/nmi_on).
NesInternalRam:72:ppumask_shadow:PPUMASK ($2001) shadow; managed by $C570 ($C567/rendering_on, $C69D/rendering_off).
NesInternalRam:73:kernel_var_73:Cleared at reset; used by $C6AD (the BRK multiply-by-3 helper)
NesInternalRam:74:palette_dirty:Non-zero = palette upload pending; $C6D4 uploads $0700-$071F to PPU $3F00-$3F1F then clears this
NesInternalRam:79:music_voice_idx:Outer-loop voice index (0-4) during music driver scan
NesInternalRam:7A:music_ptr_lo:Pointer LO into current voice record at $0734+N*9 ($7A/$7B)
NesInternalRam:7B:music_ptr_hi:Pointer HI into current voice record
NesInternalRam:80:skip_vblank_wait:Non-zero = $C537 (wait-for-VBlank) returns immediately without spinning
NesInternalRam:81:nmi_busy:Semaphore: foreground sets to 1, spin-waits for NMI to clear it. The 'wait for VBlank' handshake.
NesInternalRam:83:clock_a_hi:16-bit wall-clock A high byte; NMI adds +2 every frame (gated by $89); reset = $04 (init $04D2 = 1234)
NesInternalRam:84:clock_a_lo:Wall-clock A low byte; reset = $D2
NesInternalRam:85:clock_b_hi:16-bit wall-clock B high byte; reset = $04
NesInternalRam:86:clock_b_lo:Wall-clock B low byte; reset = $D2
NesInternalRam:89:skip_wallclock:Non-zero = NMI does OAM/audio/input but skips the wall-clock tick
NesInternalRam:B0:nmi_skip_all:Non-zero = NMI bails after OAM DMA (skips controller/palette/audio/clock)
NesInternalRam:720:audio_mute_triangle:Non-zero = triangle channel writes suppressed (for sound-effect ducking)
NesInternalRam:721:audio_active_v0:Voice 0 active flag (always $01 during song playback)
NesInternalRam:722:audio_active_v1:Voice 1 active flag
NesInternalRam:723:audio_active_v2:Voice 2 active flag
NesInternalRam:724:audio_active_v3:Voice 3 active flag
NesInternalRam:725:v0_config:Voice 0 config (3 bytes: tempo_div, song_ptr_lo, song_ptr_hi); written by audio_load_voice ($C3AD)
NesInternalRam:728:v1_config:Voice 1 config (3 bytes)
NesInternalRam:72B:v2_config:Voice 2 config (3 bytes)
NesInternalRam:72E:v3_config:Voice 3 config (3 bytes)
NesInternalRam:731:v4_config:Voice 4 config (3 bytes)
NesInternalRam:734:v0_trigger:Voice 0 byte 0: 1-4 = play on channel; 5-8 = just played (dormant); 0 = idle
NesInternalRam:73D:v1_trigger:Voice 1 byte 0 (same encoding)
NesInternalRam:746:v2_trigger:Voice 2 byte 0
NesInternalRam:74F:v3_trigger:Voice 3 byte 0
NesInternalRam:758:v4_trigger:Voice 4 byte 0
NesSaveRam:3:fief_history_table:Per-fief HIGH-WATER MARK table — 17 entries x 8 bytes each (136 bytes total at $6003-$608A). Tracks historical maxes of 4 economic stats so income harvest uses peaks, not current. FULLY DECODED 2026-05-25 from sub $A0A9 in bank 0. Per-slot layout (idx*8 from base $6003): +0=output_max, +2=dams_max, +4=loyalty_max, +6=wealth_max. Each updated via 'if current >= history: history = current' pattern. STRATEGIC IMPLICATION: stats drained by war/Train/tax don't hurt income — the peak is remembered permanently. 'Build everything to max once' is mathematically optimal because the high-water mark drives gold/rice harvest.
NesSaveRam:CF7:province_ai_state:Per-province state byte (values 0-5, 0xFF=excluded). THE eligibility gate for AI target selection: count_eligible_targets ($8172) requires !=0xFF, province_state_is_FF ($D999) tests ==0xFF, and the per-fief AI driver sub_B89B switches on it (cases 0-5). Set on ownership change by sub_98A3 ($98A3: $6CF7[fief]=arg3); cleared to 0 by many command effects. Reading 2026-05-31 showed the AI target-selection chain filters on THIS + ownership, NOT on troop men — so what writes the non-zero state (and whether it considers men/strength) is the real driver of 'which fief gets attacked'. OPEN: enumerate the state values + their setters.
NesSaveRam:D5F:config_block:4-byte config block: 01 01 02 32. Chapter 9 §4 found this lives at $6D5F-$6D65. The '02' at offset $6D63 is the value Grow subtracts from sqrt(output+amount); see const_two below.
NesSaveRam:D63:const_two:16-bit constant = 2. Read by Grow's effect handler ($87F0 at $8809) as a subtrahend in the gain calculation: regA = sqrt(output+amount) - word[$6D63]. Same constant used by Build's effect ($88A6 at $88BF). Living in the config block at $6D5F.
NesSaveRam:F0B:daimyo_turn_order:17-byte permutation of 0..16 — the daimyo turn order for the current season. Re-randomized every turn (project_nobunaga_turn_order_randomization). Read order determines who acts when within a season.
NesSaveRam:F5F:selected_province_idx:Word holding the currently-selected province index (0-16 for 17-fief scenario, 0-49 for 50-fief). The 'A4 5F 6F 8B 1A B5 8C 01 70 BB' province-access idiom (chapter 9 §4) reads this, multiplies by 26 (record size), and adds $7001 (table base) to get the record pointer. Appears 81+ times across banks 0/1/2/15. Idx=50 ($7515) is the zealot/uprising slot (header=9999 marks special).
NesSaveRam:F63:battle_defending_province:Word: the province whose tactical map is loaded for the current battle (the defender's fief). Read by map_populate ($8903, bank 2) to index province_to_mapid_table ($F70E) -> map_id -> tactical_map_cell_pool ($A57E + map_id*55, bank 4). Distinct from selected_province_idx ($6F5F). Seeding this + scenario_fief_count is sufficient to drive the ROM->SRAM map populate (render-rom-to-map.py). Session 2026-05-30.
NesSaveRam:D67:rest_turns_remaining:Per-daimyo turn-skip counter (Rest command). PINNED 2026-05-30 by driver_rest ($ADB3, Command 17): sets $6D67[d77e()] = number_input(1..10) — 'rest for N turns' (health/age recovery, ch11). The turn loop then: sub_B79B, if $6D67[daimyo]!=0, decrements one and skips the daimyo's command-pick (resting = no action this turn); the war-target planner ($A578) skips flagging a resting daimyo as prey; several other action drivers gate on it too ($8CB2/$902B/$9B52/$9C09/$9057/$B943). I.e. a resting daimyo is inert and untouchable-as-target until the counter drains.
NesSaveRam:D9D:scenario_fief_count:Word: the active scenario's fief count — 17 or 50. The 17-vs-50 selector the battle map-populate path branches on (sub_DC88: UCMPGT 50). With battle_defending_province ($6F63), the only SRAM input map_populate ($8903) needs. Session 2026-05-30.
NesSaveRam:DD4:daimyo_weakness_flag:Per-daimyo 0/1 WEAKNESS/CONDITION mark (NOT a pure war-target flag — that was an over-read, see below). WRITER (AI planning pass, bank 0 $A4AB-$A5AF): cleared to 0, then $6DD4[D] |= (rng_mod(400) < (100 - daimyo_health)) for health<=99 daimyo (gates: skip if health>99 at $A56A, or rest_turns_remaining[$6D67][D]!=0 at $A578). So P(marked) = (100-health)/400 per pass — empirically SHAPE-confirmed 2026-05-30 (flagged mean health 66.6 vs 81.9). READ BY TWO SYSTEMS: (a) war-targeting — war_helper_d972 ($D972, 'called only by War', 8 read sites incl. per-fief AI driver $B8A0) treats a marked daimyo as preferred/weak prey; (b) natural-death/health — sub_9154 ($9187) reads it in the death-roll result. RECONCILES the 2026-05-28 5-dump finding that called $6DD4 a chronic-illness/condition flag: it's a per-TURN low-health-weighted mark, but sustained-low-health daimyo (e.g. Saito) get re-marked every turn, so it LOOKS chronic across yearly dumps. **CAUTION (empirical, 2026-05-30): NOT a hard war-immunity gate** — a health>99 daimyo (never marked) was still invaded, so the mark is a PREFERENCE/vulnerability signal that biases AI targeting, not the sole war trigger. Index per-daimyo (writer loops D=0..fief_count, indexes daimyo_table_17[D] via sub_D7CD AND $6DD4[D] by same D; fief-indexed uses ride the scenario identity). Daimyo record +1 = health CONFIRMED via 50Diamyo cross-check (31/38 = start+5). Exact war role pending SRAM-dump confirmation.
NesSaveRam:E15:fief_to_daimyo_map:17-byte array, position i = current owner-daimyo idx for fief i+1 (1-based). Found 2026-05-25 via SRAM cross-reference. Initial state: identity (fief i+1 owned by daimyo i). After conquests, values change — e.g. when Tokugawa took Owari, position 16 changed from 16 (Oda) to 7 (Tokugawa). Daimyos whose value doesn't appear anywhere have lost their home; they remain in daimyo_table_17 as 'wandering' (status=$01 in chapter 7 terms, vs $00 for fief-holding lords).
NesSaveRam:1515:zealot_uprising_slot:Province-record-format slot (26 bytes, idx=50) for the zealot/Ikko-Ikki uprising force when it spawns. Uses standard 26-byte province record layout so it slots into combat engine without special-casing. Distinguishing markers: header=9999 (special), extreme loyalty/morale (1300/1516 observed), tiny skill/arms (4/4). Cleared after combat resolution. Spawn check likely lives in bank-0 season-turnover code.
NesSaveRam:1001:province_table_live:AUTHORITATIVE live working province table (chapter 9 §4 reconciliation). 17 records x 26 bytes for the 17-fief scenario. Confirmed field layout (offsets, all 16-bit LE since loadA_ind_word reads low-byte-first): +0=gold, +2=debt, +4=town, +6=rice, +8=output, +10=dams, +12=loyalty, +14=wealth, +16=men, +18=morale, +20=skill, +22=arms, +24=header (base koku, the development ceiling). Record N is at $7001 + N*26.
NesSaveRam:1A:province_table_OLD:DEPRECATED — chapter-7 identification, contradicted by chapter 9 §4 SRAM dump. The actual live province table is at $7001 (province_table_live). Kept as a label only to flag chapter-7 references for revisit.
NesSaveRam:152F:daimyo_table_17:17-fief scenario daimyo records — 17 records x 7 bytes. Each: age, Health, Drive, Luck, Charisma, IQ, status. Index parallel to daimyo_name_table at $77A8. Tokugawa is record 7 at $7560.
NesSaveRam:1560:daimyo_rec_tokugawa:Player slot in 17-fief scenario. Record 7 of daimyo_table_17. Format: age + H + D + L + Ch + IQ + status (7 bytes).
NesSaveRam:17A8:daimyo_name_table:17-fief daimyo names — 17 names x 9 bytes (8 ASCII chars + null pad). Indices parallel to daimyo_table_17. Order in 17-fief scenario: Hatakeyama, Uesugi, Hojo, Honganji, Asakura, Anekoji, Imagawa, Tokugawa, Iera, Tsutsui, Asai, Rokkaku, Kitabatake, Ashikaga, Miyoshi, Takeda, Oda. WHEN A DAIMYO IS DISPLACED AND REGENERATED (via zealot conquest, etc.), this entry is overwritten — sometimes cleanly (e.g. 'Iera' -> 'Saito'), sometimes with partial syllable-overwrite producing garbled names like 'Sate\0ui' (from 'Tsutsui'). The name regenerator may use a clean-name table with a syllable-stitch fallback.
NesSaveRam:1C00:map_tile_data:Strategic-map background tile indices. ~558 bytes covering the 18x31 map grid.
NesSaveRam:1F00:ui_transient_state:Transient UI cache: frame counter at $7FE9, animation timers, menu position, status flags. Boot bytecode zeroes $7FE7/$7FC7/$7FD3/$7FD1 on game start (chapter 6). NOT preserved across power cycles — only canonical tables survive a save.
NesSaveRam:1FE9:frame_counter:Per-frame counter (60Hz tick). Drives animation timing, cursor blink, music transitions. Continuously incremented when game is unpaused, frozen when paused.
NesInternalRam:90:palette_alt:32-byte alt palette buffer ($0090-$00AF). Used by palette_swap ($C36C, task $12) to atomically swap with palette_shadow for fade/transition effects. Reset-fill $3E (paired with palette_shadow).
NesInternalRam:700:palette_shadow:32-byte palette shadow ($0700-$071F); foreground writes here + sets palette_dirty; $C6D4 uploads to PPU $3F00 next NMI. Reset-fill $3E (medium grey).
NesPrgRom:3C000:reset_handler:Reset entry: MMC1 init via 5-write serial commit; RAM/OAM clear; APU enable; ends with JMP $8000
NesPrgRom:3C0DA:nmi_handler:NMI/VBlank handler: OAM DMA from $0600, P1+P2 polls, palette upload, music tick, wall-clock tick; bracketed by nmi_off/nmi_on
NesPrgRom:3C139:irq_handler:IRQ/BRK dispatcher: reads brk_dispatch_id, indirect-JMPs through 23-entry table at $C173
NesPrgRom:3C173:syscall_dispatch_table:23-entry JMP table (3 bytes each). Dispatched by syscall_dispatch ($F226) via the task ID at brk_dispatch_id ($0050). Chapter 4 renamed from 'BRK dispatch' — the mechanism uses PHP+JMP($FFFE), not BRK. TABLE DECODED 2026-05-31 from ROM ($C173 hex in bank_15_named.asm): 18 ids map to real handlers; id $00->reset_handler ($C000, soft-reset); ids $02/$0B/$0E/$0F are NO-OP stubs (JMP straight to an RTS) -> syscall_noop_02/_0b/_0e/_0f below. Finding the bytecode callers of the no-op ids (by task id) is a later task.
NesPrgRom:3C34B:syscall_noop_02:No-op handler for syscall id $02. The dispatch-table entry (id 2) JMPs here; body is an RTS stub (sits just before syscall_palette_write at $C34C). Unimplemented/reserved syscall — returns immediately. Walked 2026-05-31.
NesPrgRom:3C427:syscall_noop_0b:No-op handler for syscall id $0B. Dispatch-table entry (id 11) JMPs here; RTS stub (just before syscall_ppu_blit_from_bank at $C428). Unimplemented/reserved syscall. Walked 2026-05-31.
NesPrgRom:3C535:syscall_noop_0e:No-op handler for syscall id $0E. Dispatch-table entry (id 14) JMPs here; RTS stub (just before $C536/$C537=wait_vblank region). Unimplemented/reserved syscall. Walked 2026-05-31.
NesPrgRom:3C536:syscall_noop_0f:No-op handler for syscall id $0F. Dispatch-table entry (id 15) JMPs here; RTS stub. Unimplemented/reserved syscall. Walked 2026-05-31.
NesPrgRom:3C1B8:syscall_wait_for_nmi:Task $13 (id=19): set nmi_busy=1, spin until NMI clears it. The canonical 'wait for next VBlank' primitive.
NesPrgRom:3C1C3:syscall_rng_next:Task $11 (id=17): 48-bit shift-and-add transform of the wall-clock state ($0083-$0088). Returns 16-bit pseudo-random value in brk_scratch_lo/hi. The game's RNG.
NesPrgRom:3C22C:syscall_memcpy_banked:Task $10 (id=16): bank-switched memcpy. Switches to struct[2] bank, copies (struct[6:8]) -> (struct[8:10]) for length struct[10..11] (16-bit). Restores bank.
NesPrgRom:3C264:syscall_ppu_upload_block:Task $01 (id=1): bank-switched bulk copy from PRG-ROM to PPU. Switches to struct[2] bank, copies chunks of 16 bytes from (struct[6:8]) to PPU @struct[8:10]; chunk count = struct[10]. Restores bank.
NesPrgRom:3C2CB:syscall_set_sprite:Task $03 (id=3): write 1 OAM sprite. struct[2]=sprite index (0-63), struct[6]=Y, struct[8]=attr, struct[a]=tile, struct[4]=X. Writes to OAM shadow at $0600 + idx*4.
NesPrgRom:3C2F0:syscall_fill_attr_quadrant:Task $08 (id=8): fill 64 bytes of PPU attribute table. PPUADDR = $23C0 + struct[2]*4. Fill byte = struct[4].
NesPrgRom:3C312:syscall_fill_nametable:Task $05 (id=5): fill a full 30x32 nametable with one tile byte. struct[2] selects nametable; struct[4] = fill byte. Writes 960 bytes.
NesPrgRom:3C339:syscall_call_bank:Task $07 (id=7): save current bank, switch to struct[2], JSR $8000 (the bank's entry point), restore. The inter-bank call primitive.
NesPrgRom:3C34C:syscall_palette_write:Task $04 (id=4): write one palette byte. struct[2]=palette index (0-31), struct[4]=color. Writes to palette_shadow + sets palette_dirty. If skip_vblank_wait is set, writes to palette_alt instead (no NMI flag).
NesPrgRom:3C36C:syscall_palette_swap:Task $12 (id=18): atomically swap palette_shadow ($0700-$071F) with palette_alt ($0090-$00AF), gated by struct[2] XOR skip_vblank_wait. Resolves chapter-3 mystery about $0090-$00AF — it's the alt palette buffer for fade/transition effects.
NesPrgRom:3C39E:syscall_read_controller:Task $06 (id=6): read controller button state. struct[2]=player index (0=P1 from $006E, 1=P2 from $006F). Returns held buttons in brk_scratch_lo. Side effect: if any button pressed, sets skip_wallclock — game-time pauses while input is held.
NesPrgRom:3C3AD:syscall_audio_load_voice:Task $09 (id=9): set voice config. struct[2]=voice index, struct[4]=tempo_div, struct[6]=song_ptr_lo, struct[8]=song_ptr_hi. Writes 3 bytes at $0725 + voice*3 (the voice config array).
NesPrgRom:3C3CF:syscall_audio_control:Task $0A (id=10): audio control. struct[2]=voice idx, struct[4]=mode. Mode 0: silence everything (clear all voice flags + records, mute SQ1/SQ2/TRI). Mode 1: mute triangle for voice (set audio_mute_triangle+idx, clear voice trigger). Mode 2: query mute state (returns audio_mute_triangle+idx).
NesPrgRom:3C428:syscall_ppu_blit_from_bank:Task $14 (id=20): bank-switched PPU blit. Switches to bank from struct[$E] (= $005E), then writes a block from that bank to a nametable region. Used for screen content rendering (menus, maps).
NesPrgRom:3C437:syscall_ppu_blit_nobank:Task $0C (id=12): sibling of syscall_ppu_blit_from_bank but enters with mode flag = 0 (no bank switch). Falls into the same code at $C439.
NesPrgRom:3C4E0:syscall_ppu_render_rect:Task $0D (id=13): 2D nametable region renderer. struct[6/8]=start (x,y), struct[10/12]=end (x,y), struct[14]=per-tile param. Loops through every cell calling 3 helpers ($C640 compute-addr, $C673 compute-attr, $C711 write). Used for menu borders, status panels, map sections — anything with per-tile variation.
NesPrgRom:3C173:syscall_dispatch_table:23-entry kernel syscall jump table (task ids 0-22), reached via JSR $F226 (which copies the param struct from the VM stack then JMP ($FFFE) into the handler). Each entry is a 3-byte `JMP abs`. Decoded ids: 0?,1=ppu_upload_block,3=set_sprite,4=palette_write,5=fill_nametable,6=read_controller,7=call_bank,9=audio_load_voice,$10=memcpy_banked,$11=rng_next,$12=palette_swap,$13=wait_for_nmi,$14=ppu_blit_from_bank,$16=sram_block_checksum. Mirrored in tools/nobunaga_vm.SYSCALLS.
NesPrgRom:3F70E:province_to_mapid_table:Per-province -> tactical-map-id table (bank 15, fixed). map_id = F70E[province]; the cell data is then at tactical_map_cell_pool ($A57E) + map_id*55. 17-fief values [0..16] verified = [15,9,13,20,21,17,19,23,22,31,26,27,25,30,32,14,24] (Mino=22). The 50-fief path selects a parallel/extended table via scenario_fief_count. Session 2026-05-30.
NesPrgRom:3C5AA:syscall_sram_block_with_checksum:Task $16 (id=22): SRAM block read/write with 16-bit checksum. Writes 5-bit value (struct[2]) to MMC1 CHR-bank-0 register at $BFFF (SOROM WRAM-enable gate), copies ($56)->$0200 of length struct[10], writes second 5-bit value (struct[4]) to $BFFF, copies $0200->($56) while computing checksum into brk_scratch_lo/hi. The save-data I/O primitive.
NesPrgRom:3C60C:syscall_set_chr_bank0_reg:Task $15 (id=21): write 5-bit value (struct[2]) to MMC1 CHR-bank-0 register at $BFFF. On SOROM, bit 4 of this register is the WRAM-enable gate; this syscall is the bracket call that opens/closes SRAM access around save I/O.
NesPrgRom:3C577:set_prg_bank:MMC1 PRG bank switch helper. Saves NMI state, writes the 5-bit serial sequence to $FFF0 to set the bank, restores NMI state. Updates kernel_var_73 ($0073) to track current bank. Used by every bank-switching syscall.
NesPrgRom:3C558:screen_on:Re-enable display: reset PPUSCROLL to (0,0), then jsr rendering_on (PPUMASK|=$18) + jsr nmi_on (PPUCTRL|=$80). The 'turn the screen back on' helper (higher-level than rendering_on, which only flips the mask bit). Callers: b15_c238, b15_c4b5 (render-rect), b15_c757 (screen init). Walked 2026-05-31.
NesPrgRom:3C640:ppu_rect_attr_addr:ppu_render_rect ($C4E0) helper #1 of 3 (attribute-table write path). Computes the ATTRIBUTE-table byte address ($23C0-region) for a cell: addr_lo = ((y>>2)<<3)+(x>>2)+$C0, addr_hi = (nt<<2)+$23, from cell x/y ($0054/$0056) and nametable-select ($0052). Result in brk_jmp_target ($0068/$0069). Only caller: the render-rect cell loop b15_c4b5. Walked 2026-05-31 (refines the informal '$C640 compute-addr' note in syscall_ppu_render_rect).
NesPrgRom:3C673:ppu_rect_attr_shift:ppu_render_rect helper #2 of 3. Computes which 2-bit quadrant (0..3, stored in $0075) of the attribute byte this cell occupies: ((x&3)>>1) + ((y&3)>>1)*2, i.e. the 2x2 metatile sub-position. Only caller: b15_c4b5. Walked 2026-05-31 ('compute-attr').
NesPrgRom:3C711:ppu_rect_attr_rmw:ppu_render_rect helper #3 of 3 (the actual write). Read-modify-write of the attribute byte at brk_jmp_target ($0068/$0069): sets PPUADDR, reads the current byte via buffered PPUDATA, builds a 2-bit field mask from the quadrant ($0075) in $0058, splices in the new palette bits, and writes the byte back. Sets the palette for one 2x2 metatile region. Only caller: b15_c4b5. Walked 2026-05-31 ('write').
NesPrgRom:3E823:vm_entry:VM entry point. Called as JSR vm_entry from bank 0 ($A778) with inline bytecode following. Pulls 4 bytes off stack (return + previous context), allocates new VM frame (ptr1 -= 9), saves old context, sets up ptr3 (bytecode IP) and begins dispatching.
NesPrgRom:3E867:vm_dispatch:VM main dispatch loop. Reads byte at ptr3 (bytecode IP), advances ptr3, looks up handler in tables at $F026/$F126, JMPs through. Handlers do their work and JMP back here (or to a tail at $EB9E that adjusts ptr1 first).
NesPrgRom:3E87F:vm_op_00_load_offset:VM opcode $00 handler. First of 12 entries (opcodes $00-$0B) at $E87F-$E8AB, each 4 bytes apart, each loading a different immediate ($E8/$EA/.../$FE) into A then branching to the common tail at $E8AD that adds A to ptr2 and reads 16-bit data from that location.
NesPrgRom:3E8AD:vm_op_load_tail:Common tail for VM opcodes $00-$0B. Adds immediate offset to ptr2, reads 16-bit value at the resulting address, stores it as the new VM bytecode IP base ($08/$09). Used by 'load offset from ptr2' opcode group.
NesPrgRom:3EB38:vm_op_E9_host_call:VM opcode $E9: host call with VM stack adjustment. Reads next 2 bytecode bytes as a native function address, JSR through it (using the indirect-JMP-trampoline trick), then advances ptr1 before next dispatch. THIS IS THE BRIDGE FROM BYTECODE TO KERNEL — bytecode pattern 'E9 26 F2' = host_call to $F226 = syscall_dispatch.
NesPrgRom:3EB4E:vm_op_AC_host_call_simple:VM opcode $AC: simple host call without stack adjustment. Reads next 2 bytecode bytes as a native function address, JSR through it, then immediately dispatches the next opcode (no ptr1 adjustment). Different calling convention than $E9 (host call that returns no values to clean up).
NesPrgRom:3EB57:vm_call_native:VM 'JSR through ptr0' helper. Saves the VM IP onto the VM stack at ptr1, then JSRs through the indirect_jmp_trampoline ($EB7A) which executes JMP ($0000) — effectively a JSR to wherever ptr0 points. After the called native code RTS's, restores the VM stack pointer.
NesPrgRom:3EB7A:indirect_jmp_trampoline:3-byte data block '6C 00 00' = JMP ($0000). Used by vm_call_native to implement 'JSR through ptr0' which 6502 lacks natively. JSR to this block runs JMP indirect through $00/$01 (= ptr0), effectively calling whatever ptr0 points to.
NesPrgRom:3EB9E:vm_dispatch_with_ptr1_adjust:Tail used by host_call opcode $E9. Reads a byte from the bytecode as the ptr1 adjustment amount, adds it to ptr1, then enters vm_dispatch. This is the 'host call returns N bytes' cleanup convention.
NesPrgRom:3EFD5:vm_read_word_into_ptr0:VM helper: read the next 2 bytes from bytecode (at ptr3,Y=0 and ptr3,Y=1) into ptr0_lo / ptr0_hi. Advance ptr3 by 2. Used by host-call opcodes to fetch the native function address.
NesPrgRom:3F026:vm_opcode_lo_table:256-byte table of low bytes of VM opcode handler addresses, indexed by opcode byte. The full handler is at ($F126[op] << 8) | $F026[op].
NesPrgRom:3F126:vm_opcode_hi_table:256-byte table of high bytes of VM opcode handler addresses, indexed by opcode byte. Together with vm_opcode_lo_table at $F026, forms the 256-entry dispatch table for VM bytecode opcodes. Immediately precedes syscall_dispatch at $F226.
NesPrgRom:3F226:syscall_dispatch:The 22-byte parameter-copy wrapper that fakes a BRK via PHP + JMP($FFFE). Called by VM bytecode via opcode $E9 with this as the address operand. Reads syscall parameters from ($02),Y=$17..$02 — i.e. directly from the current VM frame at ptr1.
NesPrgRom:3F246:ext_op_dispatch:Extended-opcode dispatcher (VM opcode $AB). Reads the next bytecode byte as an ext-op index, *2, indexes ext_op_table ($F263), and JMPs to the handler (pushing a return into vm_dispatch). This is the 'B7 ext-op' mechanism the math32 helpers ride on.
NesPrgRom:3F263:ext_op_table:Extended-opcode address table (the 'B7 ext-op table' from the ROADMAP Inbox). ~44 little-endian handler addresses for the 16/32-bit math/logic/bitfield ops, indexed by ext_op_dispatch ($F246). Entry 0 = $F2C1 (umul32), then div/add/sub/cmp/bitfield/etc. DECODED from this ROM's own disasm 2026-05-31 — the external nesdev t=15931 spec was never needed.
NesPrgRom:3F2C1:umul32:Unsigned 32-bit multiply: A($08-$0B) * B($0C-$0F) -> product accumulated in $14-block. 32-iteration shift-add (lsr A, add B to running sum on carry, ror down). ext_op_table entry $01.
NesPrgRom:3F2FE:sdiv32_setup:Signed 32-bit divide front-end: record result sign in $40 (sign A ^ sign B) and dividend sign in $41, take |A| and |B| (via negate32_operand), then run udiv32. The signed-division ext-op.
NesPrgRom:3F31C:udiv32:Unsigned 32-bit restoring divide: A($08-$0B) / B($0C-$0F); quotient -> $08-$0B, remainder -> $10-$13. Clears the remainder hi then runs the 32-iteration shift-subtract loop at $F328.
NesPrgRom:3F427:negate32_operand:4-byte two's-complement negate of operand B ($0C-$0F): 0 - B. Used by the signed mul/div setups to take absolute value.
NesPrgRom:3F43B:test_nonzero32:Boolean-ize the 32-bit accumulator: set $08:$09 = 1 if any byte of $08-$0B is nonzero, else 0. (The $F433 sibling EORs the result with 1 = logical NOT.)
NesPrgRom:3F4C3:cmp32_a_minus_b:4-byte compare computing A($08-$0B) - B($0C-$0F) via cmp/sbc chain, leaving N/V/C/Z for the signed+unsigned comparison opcodes. Backs the lt/le/eq family at $F467-$F4C2.
NesPrgRom:3F4D6:cmp32_b_minus_a:Reversed-operand 4-byte compare B($0C-$0F) - A($08-$0B); the gt/ge sibling of cmp32_a_minus_b.
NesPrgRom:3F5CD:vm_bitfield_read:Bitfield read: load the 16-bit word at ptr0[Y], shift it right by X bits (alignment), AND with an X-wide mask from make_bitmask. Extracts a packed bitfield into $08:$09.
NesPrgRom:3F603:vm_bitfield_read_test:Reads a bitfield (vm_bitfield_read) then tests it against the inverted mask (boolean result in A / $08). Exact predicate (field != all-ones vs masked-compare) to confirm on next read; behavior verified, naming descriptive.
NesPrgRom:3F62C:vm_bitfield_write:Bitfield write/insert: build the X-wide mask (make_bitmask), shift the value left X bits, then read-modify-write the word at ptr0[Y] = (old & ~mask) | (value & mask). The packed-field setter.
NesPrgRom:3F669:make_bitmask:Build an N-bit mask (2^N - 1) into $0A:$0B, with N passed in A (rol a 1-bit at a time). Shared helper for the bitfield read/write ops.
NesPrgRom:3ECDB:vm_pop_operand16:Pop a 16-bit operand off the VM eval stack (ptr1) into operand-B low half $0C:$0D; ptr1 += 2.
NesPrgRom:3ED2E:udiv16:Unsigned 16-bit restoring divide: $08:$09 / $0C:$0D; quotient -> $08:$09, remainder -> ptr0. 16-iteration shift-subtract. (The $ECF0 sibling is the matching 16-bit multiply.)
NesPrgRom:3ED7A:sdiv16_setup_signs:Signed-divide front-end for udiv16: store the quotient sign (A^B) in $0A, take |dividend| and |divisor| in place; paired with udiv16 at the $ED1E/$ED54 signed-div opcodes.
NesPrgRom:3EF97:vm_fetch_sbyte:Fetch a signed immediate byte from the bytecode stream (ptr3),Y; sign-extend into X; ptr3++. clc on exit.
NesPrgRom:3EFA6:vm_addr_ptr2_plus_sbyte:Compute ptr0 = ptr2 + signed_byte(bytecode); ptr3++. 8-bit-signed-offset indexed addressing off base pointer ptr2.
NesPrgRom:3EFBF:vm_fetch_word:Fetch a 16-bit immediate from the bytecode (ptr3): low byte in A, high byte in X; ptr3 += 2.
NesPrgRom:3EFEC:vm_addr_ptr2_plus_word:Compute ptr0 = ptr2 + word(bytecode); ptr3 += 2. 16-bit indexed addressing off base pointer ptr2 (the array-access addressing mode).
NesPrgRom:3F2F0:sdiv32:ext_op entry $02: signed 32-bit divide A/B. jsr sdiv32_setup (|A|,|B|, divide via fall-through to udiv32, result sign in $40), then if $40<0 jmp negate32_operand. Quotient in A.
NesPrgRom:3F2FB:udiv32_entry:ext_op entry $2E: jmp udiv32 ($F31C) -- the unsigned-divide dispatch entry (3 bytes overlapping the rts tail of sdiv32 at $F2FA).
NesPrgRom:3F362:umod32:ext_op entry $2F: unsigned 32-bit remainder. jsr udiv32 (remainder->$10-$13), copy $10-$13 into A. A = A mod B, unsigned.
NesPrgRom:3F36B:smod32:ext_op entry $1E: signed 32-bit remainder. jsr sdiv32_setup, copy remainder->A, if dividend sign ($41)<0 negate. A = A mod B, sign of dividend.
NesPrgRom:3F37F:add32:ext_op entry $03: 32-bit add B += scratch. B($0C-$0F) = B + scratch($10-$13). (Targets B, the operand slot -- unlike the bitwise ops which target A.)
NesPrgRom:3F38C:sub32:ext_op entry $04: 32-bit subtract B -= scratch. B($0C-$0F) = B - scratch($10-$13).
NesPrgRom:3F399:shl32_var:ext_op entry $1F: variable left shift. A($08-$0B) <<= count($10-$13) (decrement-count loop of asl/rol).
NesPrgRom:3F3B5:shr32_var_arith:ext_op entry $20: variable arithmetic (sign-preserving) right shift. A >>= count($10-$13), sign-extended.
NesPrgRom:3F3DB:shr32_var_logical:ext_op entry $2D: variable logical (zero-fill) right shift. A = A >>> count($10-$13).
NesPrgRom:3F3F7:not32:ext_op entry $21: bitwise complement. A = ~A (one's complement, 32-bit; eor #$ff x4).
NesPrgRom:3F403:and32:ext_op entry $22: bitwise AND. A = A & B (32-bit).
NesPrgRom:3F40F:or32:ext_op entry $23: bitwise OR. A = A | B (32-bit).
NesPrgRom:3F41B:xor32:ext_op entry $24: bitwise XOR. A = A ^ B (32-bit).
NesPrgRom:3F433:logical_not32:ext_op entry $28: jsr test_nonzero32 then eor #$01 on $08 -> boolean !A (1 if A==0 else 0).
NesPrgRom:3F446:cmp32_eq:ext_op entry $06: A == B ? 1 : 0 (inline byte compare $08-$0B vs $0C-$0F; sign-agnostic).
NesPrgRom:3F457:cmp32_ne:ext_op entry $07: A != B ? 1 : 0 (inline byte compare).
NesPrgRom:3F467:cmp32_a_lt_b_signed:ext_op entry $08: A < B signed. cmp32_a_minus_b, result = N eor V.
NesPrgRom:3F475:cmp32_a_lt_b_unsigned:ext_op entry $29: A < B unsigned. cmp32_a_minus_b, result = C==0 (borrow).
NesPrgRom:3F47E:cmp32_a_gt_b_signed:ext_op entry $0A: A > B signed. cmp32_b_minus_a, result = N eor V of B-A.
NesPrgRom:3F48C:cmp32_a_gt_b_unsigned:ext_op entry $2B: A > B unsigned. cmp32_b_minus_a, C==0 of B-A.
NesPrgRom:3F495:cmp32_a_le_b_signed:ext_op entry $09: A <= B signed. cmp32_b_minus_a, inclusive (bmi) -> B>=A.
NesPrgRom:3F4A3:cmp32_a_le_b_unsigned:ext_op entry $2A: A <= B unsigned. cmp32_b_minus_a, C==1 -> B>=A.
NesPrgRom:3F4AC:cmp32_a_ge_b_signed:ext_op entry $0B: A >= B signed. cmp32_a_minus_b, inclusive (bmi) -> A>=B.
NesPrgRom:3F4BA:cmp32_a_ge_b_unsigned:ext_op entry $2C: A >= B unsigned. cmp32_a_minus_b, C==1 -> A>=B.
NesPrgRom:3F4E9:sign_extend16_to_32:ext_op entry $25: sign-extend the 16-bit value in $08:$09 to 32-bit A (fill $0A:$0B with $00/$FF from bit15).
NesPrgRom:3F4EF:clear_a_high16:ext_op entry $26: sty $0a/$0b -- zero (or Y-fill) the high half of A. Also the fall-through tail of sign_extend16_to_32.
NesPrgRom:3F4F3:ext_op_nop:ext_op entry $27: bare rts -- no-op handler.
NesPrgRom:3F4F4:load_a32_from_ptr3:ext_op entry $18: copy 4 bytes (ptr3),Y=0..3 -> A($08-$0B); reads a 32-bit inline operand and advances ptr3 by 4.
NesPrgRom:3F500:load_b32_from_ptr3:ext_op entry $19: copy 4 bytes (ptr3),Y=0..3 -> B($0C-$0F); twin of load_a32_from_ptr3 targeting B.
NesPrgRom:3F515:halve_a32_rounded:ext_op entry $1C: arithmetic divide-by-2 of A (ror/rol carry chain across $08-$0B with a sign/round seed). MED-confidence: exact rounding/sign semantic not fully traced.
NesPrgRom:3F51A:halve_a32:ext_op entry $1B: divide-by-2 of A (shares the $F515 shift body at a different carry seed). MED-confidence.
NesPrgRom:3F531:store_a32_via_popped_ptr:ext_op entry $17: jsr vm_pop_operand16 (dest ptr into $0C:$0D), then store A($08-$0B) through it.
NesPrgRom:3F53F:swap_a_b32:ext_op entry $1A: exchange A($08-$0B) with B($0C-$0F), 4 bytes.
NesPrgRom:3F54D:load_a32_from_addr:ext_op entry $0C: jsr vm_addr_ptr2_plus_word (eff. addr -> ptr0), then load (ptr0) -> A($08-$0B). Body at $F550 reused by $F57C/$F5C2.
NesPrgRom:3F55B:load_b32_from_addr:ext_op entry $0D: jsr vm_addr_ptr2_plus_word, then load (ptr0) -> B($0C-$0F). Body at $F55E reused by $F581.
NesPrgRom:3F569:store_a32_to_addr:ext_op entry $0E: jsr vm_addr_ptr2_plus_word, then store A -> (ptr0). Body at $F56C reused by $F586.
NesPrgRom:3F577:store_a32_to_addr_or_push:ext_op entry $0F: jsr vm_addr_ptr2_plus_word; carry selects push-A-onto-VM-stack ($F58E) vs store. MED-confidence: carry-variant semantic not fully traced.
NesPrgRom:3F57C:load_a32_indirect:ext_op entry $10: jsr vm_read_word_into_ptr0 (deref a word into ptr0); carry-clear -> load_a32_from_addr body ($F550). MED-confidence.
NesPrgRom:3F581:load_b32_indirect:ext_op entry $11: jsr vm_read_word_into_ptr0; carry-clear -> load_b32_from_addr body ($F55E). MED-confidence.
NesPrgRom:3F586:store_a32_indirect:ext_op entry $12: jsr vm_read_word_into_ptr0; carry-clear -> store_a32_to_addr body ($F56C). MED-confidence.
NesPrgRom:3F58B:push_value32_to_vm_stack:ext_op entry $13: jsr vm_read_word_into_ptr0, fall into $F58E: ptr1 -= 4, copy (ptr0) -> (ptr1). Pushes a 32-bit value onto the VM operand stack.
NesPrgRom:3F5A3:push_a32_to_vm_stack:ext_op entry $14: ptr0 = $0008 (address of A), jmp $F58E push primitive. Pushes accumulator A onto the VM operand stack.
NesPrgRom:3F5AC:pop_b32_from_vm_stack:ext_op entry $15: copy (ptr1),Y=3..0 -> B($0C-$0F), then ptr1 += 4. Pops a 32-bit value off the VM operand stack into B.
NesPrgRom:3F5C2:load_a32_via_a_ptr:ext_op entry $16: ptr0 = low 16 bits of A, jmp load_a32_from_addr body ($F550). Dereferences A-as-pointer into A.
NesPrgRom:3F008:vm_push16_AX:Shared 16-bit VM-stack push tail: ptr1 -= 2, store A (low) then X (high) at (ptr1), jmp vm_dispatch. 8 opcode handlers jmp here after computing a 16-bit result in A:X. The 16-bit analog of the $F58E push32 tail.
NesPrgRom:3F550:load_a32_from_ptr0:Inner body of load_a32_from_addr ($F54D): copy (ptr0),Y=3..0 -> A($08-$0B). Shared jmp-target of the indirect / A-as-pointer ext-op variants $F57C and $F5C2.
NesPrgRom:3F58E:vm_push32_tail:Shared 32-bit VM-stack push tail: ptr1 -= 4, copy (ptr0),Y=3..0 -> (ptr1). Used by ext-ops $F577 (store-or-push), $F58B (push value) and $F5A3 (push A).
